        introduction: "The 4th arrondissement of Paris is a prime departure point for reaching Orly Airport thanks to its immediate proximity to the Seine and the southern routes out of the capital. This extraordinary district brings together within a few hectares the Marais with its listed mansions, Place des Vosges with its centuries-old arcades, the Île de la Cité with Notre-Dame and the Sainte-Chapelle, as well as the Île Saint-Louis with its romantic quays. The charming hotels of the Marais attract a demanding international clientele who appreciate the quick transfer to Orly for domestic and Mediterranean flights. The 18 km journey is one of the shortest from central Paris to an airport, and the Seine quays provide a pleasant and often smooth route. Orly Airport primarily serves southern France, Corsica, the French West Indies, Spain, Portugal and North Africa — destinations highly popular with residents and visitors of the 4th arrondissement. TaxiNeo picks up travellers at any time, whether outside the Centre Pompidou, on the Hôtel de Ville square, in the lanes of the Marais or on the quays of Île Saint-Louis.",
        itineraire: "The route from the 4th arrondissement to Orly is remarkably direct thanks to the district's position along the Seine. The driver leaves the Marais via Rue Saint-Antoine or Quai de l'Hôtel de Ville and quickly reaches Pont de Sully to access Quai de la Rapée on the right bank. From there, the ring road is reached within minutes at Porte de Bercy. The A6 motorway towards Lyon is then taken for about 10 km before the Orly Airport exit leading to terminals Orly 1, 2, 3 and 4. Alternatively, if Quai de la Rapée is congested, the driver can cross the Seine at Pont d'Austerlitz and head down Boulevard de l'Hôpital towards Porte d'Italie to join the A6 from the south. A third option, often chosen in the morning, takes the left bank river roads from Pont Saint-Michel then Boulevard des Maréchaux via Porte d'Orléans. The total journey is 18 km and takes about 30 minutes outside peak hours, 40-50 minutes during busy periods.",
        conseils: "For an efficient transfer from the 4th arrondissement to Orly, here are our practical tips. Allow 2.5 hours before an international flight and 2 hours for a domestic flight from Orly. The Marais is partly pedestrianised; check that your pickup street is accessible by car. Rue de Rivoli and Rue Saint-Antoine are always accessible, while Rue des Rosiers and some medieval lanes are not. For Île Saint-Louis, the driver accesses via Pont de Sully or Pont Marie and can briefly stop on Quai d'Anjou. On Sundays, allow 10 extra minutes as Marais streets are very busy. For departures before 6am, the district is quiet and the journey takes only 22 minutes. Remember to check your Orly terminal before departure: the airport has 4 terminals and a mistake can cost time. Child seats are available free of charge on request when booking.",
        comparaisonTransport: "From the 4th arrondissement, the journey to Orly by public transport goes via metro line 1 or 7 to Châtelet then RER B to Antony and Orlyval (€14.40 per person, about 55 min). The Orlybus from Denfert-Rochereau requires a prior metro line 4 or RER B ride (€11.50 + metro, 50 min total). Tram T7 from Villejuif is very slow (1h20 from the 4th). The extended line 14 now offers a direct connection to Orly from Châtelet (about €12, 40 min). A ride-hailing service costs between €35 and €70 depending on demand. TaxiNeo guarantees a flat rate of €36 to €45 for 4 passengers, or €9 per person. It is the fastest and most comfortable solution, with no connections or stairs with suitcases.",
