        description: "The 6th arrondissement, a beacon of Parisian elegance with Saint-Germain-des-Prés, the Luxembourg Garden and the Odéon, offers access to CDG via Boulevard Saint-Michel and northern routes. Your TaxiNeo driver picks you up at your address and takes you to your terminal in about 50 minutes.",
        routeDescription: "From the 6th arrondissement, the driver heads up Boulevard Saint-Michel then Boulevard de Sébastopol northward. They join Porte de la Chapelle and the A1 motorway to Roissy. Alternatively, via the Seine quays then Porte de Bagnolet and the A3.",
        introduction: "The 6th arrondissement of Paris embodies the French art of living at its most refined. Saint-Germain-des-Prés, whose abbey church founded in the 6th century is the oldest in Paris, was the heart of intellectual and artistic life in the 20th century. The legendary cafes — Café de Flore, Les Deux Magots, Brasserie Lipp — welcomed Jean-Paul Sartre, Simone de Beauvoir, Albert Camus and Boris Vian. The Luxembourg Garden, created in 1612 by Marie de Medici, spans 25 hectares with its French-style flowerbeds, octagonal basin and palace housing the Senate. The Institut de France, with its iconic dome facing the Pont des Arts, brings together the five Academies including the famous Académie Française. The art galleries on Rue de Seine, the historic bookshops on Rue de l'Odéon, the luxury boutiques on Boulevard Saint-Germain and the antique dealers of the Carré Rive Gauche make the 6th an exceptional district. Discerning travellers staying in the palaces and boutique hotels of Saint-Germain — Hôtel Lutetia, Hôtel d'Aubusson, Relais Christine — appreciate the comfortable and punctual transfer to CDG offered by TaxiNeo.",
        itineraire: "The journey from the 6th arrondissement to CDG crosses Paris from south-west to north-east. The driver leaves Saint-Germain-des-Prés via Boulevard Saint-Germain or Boulevard Saint-Michel heading north. At the Fontaine Saint-Michel, they cross the Seine via Pont Saint-Michel and join Boulevard de Sébastopol on the right bank. This north-south axis leads directly towards Gare de l'Est and Porte de la Chapelle. The A1 motorway is then taken for about 22 km, crossing Saint-Denis, Le Bourget and Roissy-en-France before reaching the CDG terminals. If Boulevard de Sébastopol or the northern ring road is congested, the driver may opt for the right bank Seine quays to Porte de Bercy, then the A4 and the A104 Francilienne to approach CDG from the east. A third option goes via Boulevard Raspail, Boulevard Montparnasse, then Porte de Bagnolet and the A3. Real-time GPS guides the driver to the fastest route. Allow 50 minutes on average and up to 70 minutes during peak hours.",
        conseils: "For a stress-free transfer from the 6th arrondissement to CDG, here are our recommendations. Saint-Germain-des-Prés has relatively wide and well-served streets; pickup is easy on Boulevard Saint-Germain, Rue de Rennes, Boulevard Raspail or Rue Bonaparte. For hotels on Rue de Seine or Rue Jacob, the driver easily accesses via Quai Malaquais or the Odéon crossroads. Addresses near the Luxembourg Garden are accessible via Rue de Médicis, Rue de Vaugirard or Rue Guynemer. Allow 3h15 before a long-haul flight from CDG, as the journey is slightly longer from the Left Bank. Boulevard Saint-Germain is often congested between 8-9:30am on weekdays; prefer departure before 7am or after 10am. For evening or very early morning departures, the district is calm and the journey takes only 40 minutes. Remember to check your CDG terminal: T1, T2 (2A to 2G) and T3 are far apart from each other.",
        comparaisonTransport: "From the 6th arrondissement, the RER B is accessible from Luxembourg station, just minutes on foot from the Luxembourg Garden (€12.10 per person, 40-45 min direct to CDG). This is one of the best Left Bank connections. However, the RER B is frequently disrupted and crowded with luggage. Denfert-Rochereau station is also nearby for the RER B. The Roissybus from Opéra requires a 20-minute metro ride (€16.60, 60-75 min). A ride-hailing service costs between €55 and €95 depending on time and demand. TaxiNeo offers a guaranteed flat rate of €53 to €65 for 4 passengers, about €13 per person. For travellers with luggage, the taxi is incomparably more comfortable than the RER, with direct pickup from your Saint-Germain hotel.",
